<p>Swift River ("Swfit") is a Free and Open Source tool for crowdsourced situational awareness.</p>

<p>Swift builds on Twitter Vote Report, election monitoring application that lets voters report voting irregularities. Titter Vote Report was particularly innovative because it relied on real people reviewing and refining the reports into reusable data. Anyone could register to be a "Sweeper" who converted phone calls and SMS messages into machine-readable format. This allowed for unprecedented visualizations of the election in real time, created entirely by citizens.
</p>

<p>In this way, Swift hopes to organize and republish data by letting "crowds" of interested people tag information as it is received. The goal is to create a responsive news tool that allows "citizen editors" to curate structured data about an emergent topic. Theoretically, Swift could be used to organize a team around any topic, but the developers of Swift are particularly interested in crisis reporting (<a href="http://ushahidi.com">Ushahidi</a>) and international media criticism (<a href="http://meedan.net">Meedan</a>).</p>

